# ============================================================================
# _fipsctl — zsh completion for the **three companion binaries** that ship
#             with jmcorgan/fips — the "Free Internetworking Peering
#             System", a Rust mesh-routing daemon that builds an
#             encrypted overlay network over arbitrary transports
#             (UDP, TCP, Ethernet, Tor, Bluetooth LE) addressed by
#             Nostr secp256k1 public keys.  The existing `_fips`
#             completion covers the main daemon; this file covers
#             `fipsctl` (control client), `fipstop` (TUI monitor),
#             and `fips-gateway` (Linux-only outbound LAN gateway).
#             Rust=166 OPENING leg of new Axis 111 (Nostr protocol)
#             via the canonical Rust Nostr SDK `nostr-sdk`.
# ============================================================================
#
# UPSTREAM
#   Repository : https://github.com/jmcorgan/fips
#   Maintainer : Johnathan Corgan  <jcorgan@corganlabs.com>
#   License    : MIT
#   Stars      : 187
#   Language   : Rust
#   Crate      : fips, version 0.4.0-dev
#   Binaries   : fips           (mesh routing daemon — already
#                                covered by `_fips`)
#                fipsctl        (control client; speaks JSON over
#                                a Unix domain socket on Unix or
#                                TCP on Windows)
#                fipstop        (ratatui TUI dashboard)
#                fips-gateway   (Linux-only outbound LAN gateway
#                                using nftables NAT + .fips DNS)
#   Last push  : 2026-06-02
#
# WHAT IT IS
#   FIPS ("Free Internetworking Peering System") is an encrypted
#   mesh-routing overlay where nodes are identified by Nostr
#   secp256k1 pubkeys (the bech32 `npub1…` form is the
#   "address"), authenticated via Nostr `nip-59` gift-wrapped
#   events, and routed across heterogenous transports — UDP,
#   TCP, raw Ethernet, Tor, and Bluetooth LE — with automatic
#   key management.  Each FIPS node runs the `fips` daemon
#   which exposes a TUN device (`fips0` virtual interface) and a
#   `.fips` mDNS-style name resolver, so applications speak
#   plain IPv6 over the mesh and the daemon transparently
#   handles transport selection, hop-by-hop encryption (HKDF +
#   ChaCha20-Poly1305 + secp256k1 ECDH), spanning-tree path
#   computation, and bloom-filter dedup.
#
#   The three CLI tools in this completion file are FIPS's
#   operator surface:
#
#     fipsctl       Sends JSON commands to the running `fips`
#                   daemon's control socket and pretty-prints the
#                   response.  Subcommands: `show`, `acl`,
#                   `keygen`, `connect`, `disconnect`, `stats`.
#
#     fipstop       A ratatui-based full-screen TUI monitor —
#                   like `htop` for the FIPS mesh.  Polls the
#                   daemon over the same control socket at a
#                   configurable refresh interval and renders
#                   tabbed panels: Node / Peers / Links / Tree /
#                   Sessions / Graphs / Gateway.
#
#     fips-gateway  A Linux-only systemd-style daemon that lets
#                   unmodified LAN hosts reach FIPS mesh
#                   destinations via DNS-allocated virtual IPs +
#                   kernel nftables NAT.  Plain LAN clients see
#                   `<peer>.fips` names resolving to NAT-pool
#                   IPs; nftables rules forward those packets
#                   into the mesh.
#
# CLI ARGUMENT GRAMMAR  (verbatim from src/bin/{fipsctl.rs,
#                       fipstop/main.rs,fips-gateway.rs} clap
#                       derive structs; extracted via
#                       `gh api repos/jmcorgan/fips/contents/
#                       src/bin/…`)
#
#   ════════════════ fipsctl ════════════════
#
#   fipsctl [OPTIONS] <COMMAND>
#
#   Options:
#     -h, --help                     Show help
#     -V, --version                  Print version
#     -s, --socket <PATH>            Control socket path override
#
#   Commands:
#     show <WHAT>                    Show node information
#         status                     Node status overview
#         peers                      Authenticated peers
#         links                      Active links
#         tree                       Spanning tree state
#         sessions                   End-to-end sessions
#         bloom                      Bloom filter state
#         mmp                        MMP metrics summary
#         cache                      Coordinate cache stats
#         connections                Pending handshake connections
#         transports                 Transport instances
#         routing                    Routing table summary
#         identity-cache             Identity cache entries
#                                     (known node pubkeys)
#     acl <WHAT>                     Show peer ACL information
#         show                       Loaded peer ACL state
#     keygen [OPTIONS]               Generate a new FIPS identity
#                                    keypair (secp256k1)
#         -d, --dir <DIR>            Output dir for fips.key +
#                                    fips.pub
#                                    [default: /etc/fips on Unix]
#         -f, --force                Overwrite existing key files
#         -s, --stdout               Print nsec and npub to
#                                    stdout instead of writing
#                                    files
#     connect <PEER> <ADDRESS> <TRANSPORT>
#                                    Connect to a peer
#                                      PEER:      npub bech32 or
#                                                 /etc/fips/hosts
#                                                 alias
#                                      ADDRESS:   transport addr
#                                                 (e.g. 1.2.3.4:2121)
#                                      TRANSPORT: udp | tcp | tor |
#                                                 ethernet
#     disconnect <PEER>              Disconnect a peer
#     stats <WHAT>                   Query historical node stats
#         list                       List available history metrics
#         peers                      List peers tracked in stats
#         history <METRIC> [OPTS]    Fetch a time-series window
#             --peer <PEER>          Peer npub or hostname
#             --window <DURATION>    Window — Ns, Nm, Nh
#                                    [default: 10m]
#             --granularity <RES>    1s (fast ring) or 1m (slow
#                                    ring)  [default: 1s]
#             --plot                 Render a Unicode block
#                                    sparkline instead of JSON
#
#   ════════════════ fipstop ════════════════
#
#   fipstop [OPTIONS]
#
#   Options:
#     -h, --help                     Show help
#     -V, --version                  Print version
#     -s, --socket <PATH>            Control socket path override
#     --gateway-socket <PATH>        Gateway control socket override
#     -r, --refresh <SECONDS>        Refresh interval in seconds
#                                    [default: 2]
#
#   ════════════════ fips-gateway ════════════════
#
#   fips-gateway [OPTIONS]   (Linux-only; on macOS/Windows the
#                             binary exists but exits with 1)
#
#   Options:
#     -h, --help                     Show help
#     -V, --version                  Print version
#     -c, --config <FILE>            Path to configuration file
#                                    (overrides default search)
#     -l, --log-level <LEVEL>        Log level
#                                    [trace, debug, info, warn,
#                                     error; default: info]
#
# AXIS / CORPUS POSITION
#   `fips` crate declares **direct** dependencies on
#   `nostr = "0.44"` (with `nip59` feature) and
#   `nostr-sdk = "0.44"` in its `Cargo.toml` (verified via
